      <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong>2. Overdue Item Resolution:</strong> All overdue work orders should be reviewed within five business days of this report. A root cause analysis should be performed for recurring overdue patterns, and corrective actions documented in the vessel management system.</p>

      <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong>3. Resource Allocation:</strong> Vessels with compliance rates below 80% should be assessed for resource constraints. Additional support, parts procurement, or scheduling adjustments may be required to bring compliance back to acceptable levels.</p>

      <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong>4. Regulatory Alignment:</strong> Ensure that all work order categories align with current regulatory requirements and classification society standards. Any changes to regulatory frameworks should be reflected in work order templates and compliance criteria.</p>

      <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong>5. Crew Training:</strong> Where work order delays are attributed to knowledge gaps or procedural issues, targeted training should be scheduled to ensure the crew can effectively complete required maintenance and inspection tasks.</p>

      <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><strong>6. Documentation Standards:</strong> Maintain thorough documentation of all work order activities, completion evidence, and any deviations from scheduled maintenance. Complete records are essential for audits, inspections, and Port State Control examinations.</p>
